Award <marks>1</marks> mark for each correct explanation up to <marks>4</marks> marks max:

- **Definition**: Automatic memory management that reclaims unused memory;
- **Purpose**: Prevents memory leaks by deallocating objects no longer referenced;
- **Programmer benefit**: Reduces programming errors (like manual deallocation errors) and simplifies memory management;
- **System benefit**: Prevents memory exhaustion and improves system stability;
- **Process**: Identifies unreachable objects and frees their memory automatically;

Award <marks>1</marks> mark for each valid comparison/point up to <marks>4</marks> marks max:

**Mark-and-sweep**:
- **Process**: Periodically marks reachable objects starting from roots, then sweeps/deallocates unreachable ones;
- **Advantages**: Successfully handles circular references and ensures thorough cleanup;
- **Disadvantages**: Can cause a "stop-the-world" pause during collection and has higher execution overhead during the sweep phase;

**Reference counting**:
- **Process**: Maintains a counter for the number of references to each object; deallocates when the count reaches zero;
- **Advantages**: Provides immediate deallocation of memory and distributes overhead throughout the program execution;
- **Disadvantages**: Cannot handle circular references and requires constant overhead to update counts on every assignment;

Award <marks>1</marks> mark for each correct language up to <marks>2</marks> marks max:

- Java;
- C#;
- Python;
- JavaScript;
- Kotlin;
- Scala;
